## Before immediately deleting all rows that have missing data it 
##may be instructive to find where they are first
#function to return number of columns containing NAs
#base::complete.cases() operates on rows
na_col_count <- function(df){
  na.v <- sapply(df, function(x) any(is.na(x)))
  sum(na.v)
}  

print(paste('Number of rows containing NA values: ', sum(!complete.cases(nyc_df))))
## [1] "Number of rows containing NA values:  72"
print(paste('Number of columns containing NA values: ', na_col_count(nyc_df)))
## [1] "Number of columns containing NA values:  28"
#function to return dataframe of columns by NA count
#trim=F also displays complete columns
na_col_sums <- function(df, trim=T){
  nacols.df <- as.data.frame(sapply(df, function(x) sum(is.na(x))))
  names(nacols.df) <- 'NAs'                         
  nacols.df <- nacols.df[order(-nacols.df$NAs), , drop=F] 
  #default drop=T returns vector from 1-col df subset
  nacols.df$Percent_of_DFrows <- round(100*nacols.df$NAs/nrow(df), 2)
  nacols.df$Percent_of_NArows <- round(100*nacols.df$NAs/sum(!complete.cases(df)), 2)
  names(nacols.df) <- c('NAs', 'Percent of Column', 'Percent of Incomplete Rows')
  if(!trim){return(nacols.df)}else{ 
    nacols.df <- nacols.df[nacols.df$NAs != 0, ]
    nacols.df
  }                           
}

na_col_sums(nyc_df)

#function to filter rows containing NAs
##lim = 0.2 will filter rows where 20% of columns are NA or less, 
#etc. Default lim=0
#keep=T returns the removed rows instead of the cleaned dataframe
row_nafilter <- function(df, keep=F, lim=0){
  row_v <- apply(df, 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x))/length(x) <= lim)
  if(keep){
    df[!row_v, ]
  }else{
    df[row_v, ]
  }
}
#Count Of NA's remain now as 27
nyc_na_df <- row_nafilter(nyc_df, keep=T)
nyc_df <- nyc_df[!is.na(nyc_df$ChildPoverty), ]
nyc_df <- row_nafilter(nyc_df, lim=0.2)

##Descriptive Statistics on Cleansed Dataset
median_ChildPov <- median(nyc_df$ChildPoverty)
UQ_ChildPov <- quantile(nyc_df$ChildPoverty, )[4]
LQ_ChildPov <- quantile(nyc_df$ChildPoverty)[2]


#Columns ChildPoverty_AA, Childpoverty_UQ and ChildPoverty_LQ are added using Mutate
#These will indicate whether the rate of child poverty in 
#that census tract is above average (median), in the upper quartile or in the
#lower quartile respectively

nyc_df <- nyc_df %>%
  mutate(ChildPoverty_AA = ChildPoverty > median_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(ChildPoverty_UQ = ChildPoverty >= UQ_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(ChildPoverty_LQ = ChildPoverty <= LQ_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate_at(.vars = vars(Men, Women, Citizen, Employed), 
            .funs = funs(round(.*100/TotalPop, 1))) %>%
  select(-County)

#function to group a column and modify it by a summarise() function e.g. mean() or sum()
#replace=T deletes the column being modified
mod_col_by_group <- function(df, groupcol, modcol, f, colname='NewCol', replace=F){
  gcol <- enquo(groupcol)
  mcol <- enquo(modcol)
  mod_df <- df %>% group_by(!!gcol) %>% summarise(NewCol = f(!!mcol))
  df <- merge(df, mod_df, all.x = T) %>% rename_(.dots = setNames('NewCol', colname))
  if(!replace){return(df)}else{
    df <- df %>% select(-!!mcol)
  }
}

nyc_coord.df <- mod_col_by_group(nyc_coord.df, CensusTract,
                                 Latitude, mean, 'LatMean', replace=T)
nyc_coord.df <- mod_col_by_group(nyc_coord.df, CensusTract,
                                 Longitude, mean, 'LongMean', replace=T)
nyc_coord.df <- unique(nyc_coord.df)
nyc_df <- merge(nyc_df, nyc_coord.df, all.x=T)

##Model

randomise <- function(df){
  n <- nrow(df)
  rows.v <- sample(1:n, n)
  df[rows.v, ]
}

#randomising rows for model
nyc_df <- randomise(nyc_df)
nyc_imp.df <- cbind(nyc_df[, 3:35], nyc_df[, 'ChildPovErr'])
names(nyc_imp.df)[34] <- 'ChildPovErr'
nyc_train.df <- nyc_imp.df[1:(0.8*nrow(nyc_imp.df)), ]
nyc_test.df <-  nyc_imp.df[-(1:(0.8*nrow(nyc_imp.df))), ]

#For continuous numeric variables like MeanCommute it employs Predictive Mean Matching (PMM)
nyc_train.l <- mice(nyc_train.df, m=3, maxit = 5, method = 'pmm', seed = 500)

MODEL EVALUATION 

mean_v <- function(...){
    v.l <- list(...)
    v.m <- simplify2array(v.l)
    rowMeans(v.m)
}

predict1.v <- predict(CPov1.mod, as.matrix(nyc_test1.df[, -1]))
predict2.v <- predict(CPov2.mod, as.matrix(nyc_test2.df[, -1]))


predict.v <- mean_v(predict1.v, predict2.v)
err.v <- mean_v(nyc_err1.v, nyc_err2.v)[-(1:(0.8*length(nyc_err1.v)))]
error.df <- data_frame(actual=nyc_test1.df[, 1],
                       error=err.v,
                      predicted=predict.v,
                      residual=nyc_test.df[, 1] -predict.v)
                    
error.df <- error.df %>% mutate(actual_UQ = actual>=UQ_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(predicted_UQ = predicted>=UQ_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(match_UQ = actual_UQ==predicted_UQ) %>% 
  mutate(actual_AA = actual>=median_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(predicted_AA = predicted>=median_ChildPov) %>%
  mutate(match_AA = actual_AA==predicted_AA) %>%
  mutate(within_err = (predicted > (actual-error)) & (predicted < (actual+error)) )

head(error.df)
## # A tibble: 6  11
##   actual error predicted resid actua predi match actua predi match
##    <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl> <lgl>   <lgl>   <lgl>   <lgl>   <lgl>   <lgl>  
## 1   15.3 2.47      30.4    4040. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   TRUE    FALSE  
## 2    2.8 0.954     15.7    3912. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   FALSE   TRUE   
## 3    1.4 0.298      5.71   6912. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   FALSE   TRUE   
## 4    0   0          9.92   3452. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   FALSE   TRUE   
## 5   15.3 1.45      30.3    4682. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   TRUE    FALSE  
## 6    2.1 0.702     10.6    3302. FALSE   FALSE   TRUE    FALSE   FALSE   TRUE   
## #  with 1 more variable: within_err <lgl>, and abbreviated variable names
## #   residual, actual_UQ, predicted_UQ, match_UQ, actual_AA, predicted_AA,
## #   match_AA
UQ_sum <- as.numeric(summary(error.df$match_UQ)[2:3])
AA_sum <- as.numeric(summary(error.df$match_AA)[2:3])
err_sum <- as.numeric(summary(error.df$within_err)[2:3])

print(paste('Model prediction success for detecting high child poverty:',
     (100*UQ_sum[2])/(UQ_sum[1] + UQ_sum[2]), '%'))
## [1] "Model prediction success for detecting high child poverty: 84.1232227488152 %"
print(paste('Model prediction success for detecting above average child poverty:',
     (100*AA_sum[2])/(AA_sum[1] + AA_sum[2]), '%'))
## [1] "Model prediction success for detecting above average child poverty: 78.436018957346 %"
print(paste('Model prediction within error estimate for actual value:',
     (100*err_sum[2])/(err_sum[1] + err_sum[2]), '%'))
## [1] "Model prediction within error estimate for actual value: 31.9905213270142 %"
